{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17520951","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17520951"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:31:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:31:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13546"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13546","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13546"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.65,0.08,0.1,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6161"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55204"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6161","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6161"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13546"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40722"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1106"},{"type":"tags","id":"1111"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"1150"},{"type":"tags","id":"1360"},{"type":"tags","id":"1731"},{"type":"tags","id":"2355"},{"type":"tags","id":"2356"},{"type":"tags","id":"4952"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11624"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11256"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12257"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35545"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41938"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55204","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55204"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department brought in by ambulance after being found agitated in a park by bystanders. He complains of headache, chest pain, generalised muscle cramps, shivers and sweats. He has vomited twice. When questioned, he admits to taking a number of unknown tablets, which resulted in him feeling more sociable and connected to others.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 130/min, blood pressure 180/110 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 97% on room air, and temperature 38.7\u00b0C. He is diaphoretic, agitated and confused with dilated pupils. The patient is experiencing visual hallucinations, as well as paranoid delusions regarding his family members. There is generalised hyperreflexia, muscle rigidity and inducible clonus, most noticeable in the lower extremities.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following recreational drugs is the patient most likely to have taken?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cocaine","MDMA (ecstasy)","Gamma-hydroxybutyrate (GHB)","Psilocybin (\u0027magic mushrooms\u0027)","Tramadol"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is presenting with classical symptoms of a stimulant overdose, including headache, chest pain, vomiting and muscle cramps. Examination findings are also in keeping with a stimulant, including tachycardia, hypertension, diaphoresis, fever, mydriasis and hallucinations. The patient is also showing signs of serotonin syndrome, evident by hyperreflexia, muscle rigidity, clonus and autonomic hyperactivity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMDMA\u003C/strong\u003E (ecstasy) is the most likely drug responsible for this presentation. MDMA is an \u0027empathogen\u0027 with stimulant effects, often consumed orally as tablets. It stimulates the release of neurotransmitters, particularly serotonin and noradrenaline. This accounts for the patient\u0027s feelings of increased sociability and connectedness, as well as the symptoms of serotonin syndrome. The presentation is consistent with MDMA\u0027s known effects, including autonomic hyperactivity, neuromuscular abnormalities, and altered mental status.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECocaine\u003C/strong\u003E is a stimulant that can cause similar physiological effects to MDMA and can potentially cause serotonin syndrome. However, it is most commonly snorted in the form of a white powder and not commonly taken in tablet form. Additionally, it does not typically produce the empathogenic effects described by the patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGamma-hydroxybutyrate\u003C/strong\u003E (GHB) is a depressant drug. Its effects would be opposite to those seen in this patient, typically causing drowsiness, bradycardia, and respiratory depression. Therefore, it is not a likely cause of this presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPsilocybin\u003C/strong\u003E (\u0027magic mushrooms\u0027) is a hallucinogen that can cause euphoria, altered mood, mydriasis, and autonomic hyperactivity. While it can cause some similar symptoms, it is not associated with serotonin syndrome and doesn\u0027t typically have the pronounced empathogenic effects seen with MDMA. Psilocybin is found in high concentration in mushrooms from the genus Psilocybe and whilst it can be processed into a dry powder to be ingested in a capsule, this is uncommon and it is most typically consumed by directly eating the mushroom. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETramadol\u003C/strong\u003E is an opioid medication and serotonin-norepinephrine reuptake inhibitor (SNRI). While it could theoretically cause serotonin syndrome, especially in combination with other serotonergic drugs, its primary effects as an opioid (respiratory depression, confusion, miosis) are opposite to what is seen in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn conclusion, the combination of stimulant effects, serotonin syndrome, and empathogenic experience most strongly points to MDMA as the causative agent in this case.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["MDMA (ecstasy) can cause serotonin syndrome, characterized by autonomic hyperactivity, neuromuscular abnormalities, and altered mental status.","Stimulant drugs like MDMA can cause symptoms such as tachycardia, hypertension, hyperthermia, diaphoresis, and mydriasis.","MDMA is known for its empathogenic effects, increasing feelings of sociability and connectedness."],"references":["Alcohol and Drug Foundation. Drug Wheel [Internet]. 08 Nov 23. Available from: https://adf.org.au/drug-facts/#wheel","Li W, Gunja N. Illicit drug overdose prevalence and acute management. Aust Fam Physician. 2013; 42(7). Available from: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2013/july/illicit-drug-overdose"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40722"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13546"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40722","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/40722"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-14T08:18:33+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-14T08:19:38+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6161"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55204"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGr